{"name":"System Performance Parameters","id":70,"content":"<div style=\"background:#eeeeee;border:1px solid #cccccc;padding:5px 10px;\"><em>How do you measure that your system is very good? If your system responds within 1 second if I ask it for something, does it mean that it is Good?</em></div>\n\n<p>There are many parameters on which system performance is measured.</p>\n\n<ul>\n\t<li>Short&nbsp;<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Response_time_(technology)\" title=\"Response time (technology)\">response time</a>&nbsp;for a given piece of work.&nbsp;</li>\n\t<li>High&nbsp;<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Throughput\" title=\"Throughput\">throughput</a>&nbsp;(rate of processing work). How many requests can it process per hour, for example?</li>\n\t<li>Low utilization of&nbsp;<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Computing_resource\" title=\"Computing resource\">computing resource</a>(s)</li>\n\t<li><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/High_availability\" title=\"High availability\">High availability</a>&nbsp;of the computing system or application. When I ask for something it should respond (<em>at least</em>) every time.</li>\n\t<li>Fast (or highly compact)&nbsp;<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Data_compression\" title=\"Data compression\">data compression</a>&nbsp;and decompression.</li>\n\t<li>High&nbsp;<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bandwidth_(computing)\" title=\"Bandwidth (computing)\">bandwidth</a>&nbsp;(how much data can be transferred at max, per hour&nbsp;for example).</li>\n\t<li>Short&nbsp;<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Data_transmission\" title=\"Data transmission\">data transmission</a>&nbsp;time.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h2><span style=\"font-family:Lucida Sans Unicode,Lucida Grande,sans-serif;\">Round Trip Time (Response Time for a single transaction)</span></h2>\n\n<p><font face=\"Lucida Sans Unicode, Lucida Grande, sans-serif\">This depends on the following:-</font></p>\n\n<ol>\n\t<li>Network I/O Time: for transfer and disseminating data between servers and to the correct location within the system.</li>\n\t<li>Disk I/O Time: for enrollment when the transaction reaches the correct stage of enrollment.</li>\n\t<li>CPU Load over a number of cores at various stages</li>\n\t<li>Speed and performance of DBMS running over your physical machines.</li>\n\t<li>Right Amount of DB partitioning for in-memory search and response time within various stages of a multi-stage system.</li>\n\t<li>The correct amount of RAM on each server, based on what the software processes running on them require, to reduce cost, but avoid allowing the OS to utilize virtual memory page swapping to disk.</li>\n</ol>\n\n<h2><span style=\"font-family:Lucida Sans Unicode,Lucida Grande,sans-serif;\">Total Transaction Throughput (Number of Transactions per Second)</span></h2>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n","authorId":null,"subject":"architectures","tags":null,"img":null,"summary":"","lastUpdated":"2020-04-11T14:58:35.726+0000"}